Thanks also to our patrons who are financially supporting our videos, you're essentially the co-producers - thank you legends! snippet.textDisplay:
The water in Long Island in the summer isn't that cold. You need to go up to Maine (or anywhere north of Cape Cod).


I sympathize with fishermen and the loss of fishing grounds, but, if you think about it, they are hunting for a living. They should be farming the fish. We don't really expect people to go out and hunt for meat (shooting a wild steer), and then sell it to the super market, but that's what they are doing when they fish.

snippet.textDisplay:
Actually guys if you take one of your corn cobs, after eating the corn off yourself, and put just the cob(s) in a baggie in the freezer. Then later when Lenny is teething give it to him and he'll get huge relief from chewing on the cold cob. It really works we have 6 kids and they've all done that to great effect. (Gives Mom and Dad relief as well from feeling so bad for the little one as they teeth, such a helpless feeling sometimes.) Just thought I'd mention it as I thought of it when I saw Lenny munchin' on Elayna's corn cob in this video. Hope you try it out and it serves you as well as it served our family over the years.
PS: you obviously still have to watch the little one as sometimes they end up actually biting the end pieces off but you just fish 'em out of the mouth and give 'em back the big cob. As always little ones must be SAFETY WATCHED as you well know by now :) On a boat .....OOOOH MY......
Thanks for your great videos and keep up the good work . :) I really hope you read and like this idea as it really does work.

snippet.textDisplay:
WATER IN YOUR DIESEL
Hey Guys....Riley, if you read this.
As you said Riley, getting water in your diesel, is not uncommon, and actually is very common to pick up a little water, each time you fuel! Especially on very remote, out of the way, fuel docks, in the tropics. As they have very old tanks with leaks...and they don't sell large enough volumes of fuel. To use up, and refurbish their fuel stocks...so, water accumulates in the fuel you buy.

Here's the problem. Believe it or not. In the warm tropics, bacteria will grow in the water in your fuel tanks. Making a ribbon in your tank, that looks like 3/4 masking tape.

Then when your fuel gets low...or...your in a major storm. That ribbon will slosh around. Get sucked into the pipe, leading to your fuel filters. Plugging the filters, and or, the fuel line itself. Starving the engines for fuel as the filters get full of the masking tape looking bacteria residue.

When we took our 62' sailboat, from Seattle, down thru Mexico. Thru the canal. We had to motor alot thru Mexico, because there was absolutely no wind. So we fueled where we could. I mean, we've even gotten refueled in remote places, where the local fuel docks, have been waiting for a couple months, for a new replacement elecrtic fuel pump to come in. Soo...we had to hire a local pick up truck owner. That had some old 50gal barrels, to drive to a gad station, to buy fuel for us. In another really remote area, we got fueled up, off the beach. Carrying a 50 gallon barrel in our dinghy.

Well....we couldn't keep our fuel filters clean, from filling up with this bacteria crud. We went thru a ton of filters. There was a very large sail boat that went over the reef, out in Tahiti, or someplace. Because they couldn't start their engines...they surmise, they had bacteria fuel fouling. The storm hit...the boat was a goner.

In Costa Rica, the Costa Rican Navy explained to us about diesel bacteria, in the water in the fuel. Then they gave us a quart, of fuel additve they use.
That each time you fuel...you add, like 2 ounces, per 100 gallons. And it will kill the bacteria, and also cause the water to immerse back into the diesel fuel.

BINGO...no more plugged fuel fitler changes, rolling around out in an ocean storm. You can buy the diesel additive in the tropics, at most marine stores, in the tropics. Where its a very common problem.

Sooo....just add a little, in each fuel up. Problem solved!!! AND.....you no longer have to worry about, having a plug put in the bottom of your fuel tanks, to drain out water. Nor siphoning it put like you did.

That additive, will keep the water, molecularly in solution, in the fuel. So it will harmlessly, pass thru your filters, and fuel injectors on the engine.
AND...with the water still in suspension, bacteria can't grow in your fuel. AND...you won't have to siphon water out of your tanks!

Jeffery

snippet.textDisplay: That last moment where the squirrel is right behind Lennon/Lenny is SOOO funny - unless the squirrel ended up biting him!   Ahhhh!    Besides all that, back in the mid 1960s my dad and my 2 older brothers went fishing off of the south shore at or near Montauk, Long Island.  We did okay (I caught the most fish - two flounders).  But it got very foggy and my dad had to pilot our very basic 12 foot boat - with a 5 hp motor - back to the boat launch by the sound of the fog horn.  I think he was a little scared but he hid it pretty well.  But my brothers and I all learned a lesson about how good a fog horn can be.  They are like a light house but using sound instead of light (obviously).                        Scott W
